<doc id="285773" wikidata="Q847204" url="?curid=285773" title="Limit of a sequence">
<text>As the positive integer formula_1 becomes larger and larger, the value formula_2 becomes arbitrarily close to formula_3. We say that &quot;the limit of the sequence formula_4 equals formula_3.&quot;


In mathematics, the limit of a sequence is the value that the terms of a sequence &quot;tend to&quot;, and is often denoted using the formula_6 symbol (e.g., formula_7). If such a limit exists and is finite, the sequence is called convergent. A sequence that does not converge is said to be divergent. The limit of a sequence is said to be the fundamental notion on which the whole of mathematical analysis ultimately rests.

Limits can be defined in any metric or topological space, but are usually first encountered in the real numbers.

==History==
The Greek philosopher Zeno of Elea is famous for formulating paradoxes that involve limiting processes.

Leucippus, Democritus, Antiphon, Eudoxus, and Archimedes developed the method of exhaustion, which uses an infinite sequence of approximations to determine an area or a volume. Archimedes succeeded in summing what is now called a geometric series.

Grégoire de Saint-Vincent gave the first definition of limit (terminus) of a geometric series in his work &quot;Opus Geometricum&quot; (1647): &quot;The &quot;terminus&quot; of a progression is the end of the series, which none progression can reach, even not if she is continued in infinity, but which she can approach nearer than a given segment.&quot;

Pietro Mengoli anticipated the modern idea of limit of a sequence with his study of quasi-proportions in &quot;Geometriae speciosae elementa&quot; (1659). He used the term &quot;quasi-infinite&quot; for unbounded and &quot;quasi-null&quot; for vanishing.

Newton dealt with series in his works on &quot;Analysis with infinite series&quot; (written in 1669, circulated in manuscript, published in 1711), &quot;Method of fluxions and infinite series&quot; (written in 1671, published in English translation in 1736, Latin original published much later) and &quot;Tractatus de Quadratura Curvarum&quot; (written in 1693, published in 1704 as an Appendix to his &quot;Optiks&quot;). In the latter work, Newton considers the binomial expansion of formula_8, which he then linearizes by &quot;taking the limit&quot; as formula_9 tends to formula_10.

In the 18th century, mathematicians such as Euler succeeded in summing some &quot;divergent&quot; series by stopping at the right moment; they did not much care whether a limit existed, as long as it could be calculated. At the end of the century, Lagrange in his &quot;Théorie des fonctions analytiques&quot; (1797) opined that the lack of rigour precluded further development in calculus. Gauss in his study of hypergeometric series (1813) for the first time rigorously investigated the conditions under which a series converged to a limit.

The modern definition of a limit (for any formula_11 there exists an index formula_12 so that ...) was given by Bernard Bolzano (&quot;Der binomische Lehrsatz&quot;, Prague 1816, which was little noticed at the time), and by Karl Weierstrass in the 1870s.

==Real numbers==
In the real numbers, a number formula_13 is the limit of the sequence formula_14, if the numbers in the sequence become closer and closer to formula_13, and not to any other number.

===Examples===

*If formula_16 for constant formula_17, then formula_18.
*If formula_19, then formula_20.
*If formula_19 when formula_22 is even, and formula_23 when formula_22 is odd, then formula_20. (The fact that formula_26 whenever formula_22 is odd is irrelevant.)
*Given any real number, one may easily construct a sequence that converges to that number by taking decimal approximations. For example, the sequence formula_28 converges to formula_29. The decimal representation formula_30 is the &quot;limit&quot; of the previous sequence, defined by formula_31
*Finding the limit of a sequence is not always obvious. Two examples are formula_32 (the limit of which is the number &quot;e&quot;) and the arithmetic–geometric mean. The squeeze theorem is often useful in the establishment of such limits.

===Definition===
We call formula_33 the limit of the sequence formula_14, which is written
:formula_35, or 
:formula_36,

if the following condition holds:
:For each real number formula_37, there exists a natural number formula_38 such that, for every natural number formula_39, we have formula_40.

In other words, for every measure of closeness formula_41, the sequence&#x27;s terms are eventually that close to the limit. The sequence formula_14 is said to converge to or tend to the limit formula_33.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_44.
If a sequence formula_14 converges to some limit formula_33, then it is convergent and formula_33 is the only limit; otherwise formula_14 is divergent. A sequence that has zero as its limit is sometimes called a null sequence.

=== Illustration ===
===Properties===
Some other important properties of limits of real sequences include the following: 
*When it exists, the limit of a sequence is unique.
*Limits of sequences behave well with respect to the usual arithmetic operations. If formula_49 and formula_50 exists, then
::formula_51
::formula_52
::formula_53
::formula_54 provided formula_55
::formula_56

*For any continuous function formula_57, if formula_58 exists, then formula_59 exists too. In fact, any real-valued function &quot;formula_57&quot; is continuous if and only if it preserves the limits of sequences (though this is not necessarily true when using more general notions of continuity).

*If formula_61 for all formula_22 greater than some formula_38, then formula_64.
*(Squeeze theorem) If formula_65 for all formula_22 greater than some formula_38, and formula_68, then formula_69.
*(Monotone convergence theorem) If formula_70 is bounded and monotonic for all formula_22 greater than some formula_38, then it is convergent.
*A sequence is convergent if and only if every subsequence is convergent.
*If every subsequence of a sequence has its own subsequence which converges to the same point, then the original sequence converges to that point.

These properties are extensively used to prove limits, without the need to directly use the cumbersome formal definition. For example, once it is proven that formula_73, it becomes easy to show—using the properties above—that formula_74 (assuming that formula_75).

===Infinite limits===

A sequence formula_14 is said to tend to infinity, written
:formula_77, or 
:formula_78,
if the following holds:
:For every real number formula_79, there is a natural number formula_38 such that for every natural number formula_39, we have formula_82; that is, the sequence terms are eventually larger than any fixed formula_79.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_84.

Similarly, we say a sequence tends to minus infinity, written
:formula_85, or
:formula_86,
if the following holds:
:For every real number formula_79, there is a natural number formula_38 such that for every natural number formula_39, we have formula_90; that is, the sequence terms are eventually smaller than any fixed formula_79.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_92.

If a sequence tends to infinity or minus infinity, then it is divergent. However, a divergent sequence need not tend to plus or minus infinity, and the sequence formula_93 provides one such example.

==Metric spaces==

===Definition===

A point formula_33 of the metric space formula_95 is the limit of the sequence formula_14 if:
:For each real number formula_37, there is a natural number formula_38 such that, for every natural number formula_39, we have formula_100.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_101.

This coincides with the definition given for real numbers when formula_102 and formula_103.

===Properties===

*When it exists, the limit of a sequence is unique, as distinct points are separated by some positive distance, so for formula_104 less than half this distance, sequence terms cannot be within a distance formula_104 of both points.

*For any continuous function &quot;f&quot;, if formula_106 exists, then formula_107. In fact, a function &quot;f&quot; is continuous if and only if it preserves the limits of sequences.

===Cauchy sequences===


A Cauchy sequence is a sequence whose terms ultimately become arbitrarily close together, after sufficiently many initial terms have been discarded. The notion of a Cauchy sequence is important in the study of sequences in metric spaces, and, in particular, in real analysis. One particularly important result in real analysis is the &quot;Cauchy criterion for convergence of sequences&quot;: a sequence of real numbers is convergent if and only if it is a Cauchy sequence. This remains true in other complete metric spaces.

==Topological spaces==

===Definition===

A point formula_108 of the topological space formula_109 is a &#x27; or &#x27; of the sequence formula_110 if:
:For every neighbourhood formula_111 of formula_33, there exists some formula_113 such that for every formula_39, we have formula_115.

This coincides with the definition given for metric spaces, if formula_95 is a metric space and formula_117 is the topology generated by formula_118.

A limit of a sequence of points formula_110 in a topological space formula_120 is a special case of a limit of a function: the domain is formula_121 in the space formula_122, with the induced topology of the affinely extended real number system, the range is formula_120, and the function argument formula_22 tends to formula_125, which in this space is a limit point of formula_121.

===Properties===

In a Hausdorff space, limits of sequences are unique whenever they exist. This need not be the case in non-Hausdorff spaces; in particular, if two points formula_33 and formula_128 are topologically indistinguishable, then any sequence that converges to formula_33 must converge to formula_128 and vice versa.

==Hyperreal numbers==
The definition of the limit using the hyperreal numbers formalizes the intuition that for a &quot;very large&quot; value of the index, the corresponding term is &quot;very close&quot; to the limit. More precisely, a real sequence formula_14 tends to &quot;L&quot; if for every infinite hypernatural formula_132, the term formula_133 is infinitely close to formula_134 (i.e., the difference formula_135 is infinitesimal). Equivalently, &quot;L&quot; is the standard part of formula_133:
:formula_137.

Thus, the limit can be defined by the formula
:formula_138.
where the limit exists if and only if the righthand side is independent of the choice of an infinite &quot;formula_132&quot;.

==Sequence of more than one index==

Sometimes one may also consider a sequence with more than one index, for example, a double sequence formula_140. This sequence has a limit formula_13 if it becomes closer and closer to formula_13 when both &quot;n&quot; and &quot;m&quot; becomes very large.

===Example===

*If formula_143 for constant formula_17, then formula_145.
*If formula_146, then formula_147.
*If formula_148, then the limit does not exist. Depending on the relative &quot;growing speed&quot; of formula_1 and formula_150, this sequence can get closer to any value between formula_10 and formula_3.

===Definition===
We call formula_33 the double limit of the sequence formula_140, written
:formula_155, or 
:formula_156,

if the following condition holds:
:For each real number formula_37, there exists a natural number formula_38 such that, for every pair of natural numbers formula_159, we have formula_160.
In other words, for every measure of closeness formula_41, the sequence&#x27;s terms are eventually that close to the limit. The sequence formula_140 is said to converge to or tend to the limit formula_33.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_164.

The double limit is different from taking limit in &quot;n&quot; first, and then in &quot;m&quot;. The latter is known as iterated limit. Given that both the double limit and the iterated limit exists, they have the same value. However, it is possible that one of them exist but the other does not.

===Infinite limits===

A sequence formula_165 is said to tend to infinity, written
:formula_166, or 
:formula_167,
if the following holds:
:For every real number formula_79, there is a natural number formula_38 such that for every pair of natural numbers formula_170, we have formula_171; that is, the sequence terms are eventually larger than any fixed formula_79.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_173.

Similarly, a sequence formula_165 tends to minus infinity, written
:formula_175, or 
:formula_176,
if the following holds:
:For every real number formula_79, there is a natural number formula_38 such that for every pair of natural numbers formula_170, we have formula_180; that is, the sequence terms are eventually smaller than any fixed formula_79.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_182.

If a sequence tends to infinity or minus infinity, then it is divergent. However, a divergent sequence need not tend to plus or minus infinity, and the sequence formula_183 provides one such example.

===Pointwise limits and uniform limits===

For a double sequence formula_165, we may take limit in one of the indices, say, formula_185, to obtain a single sequence formula_186. In fact, there are two possible meanings when taking this limit. The first one is called pointwise limit, denoted

:formula_187, or
:formula_188,

which means:

:For each real number formula_37 and each fixed natural number formula_190, there exists a natural number formula_191 such that, for every natural number formula_39, we have formula_193.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_194.

When such a limit exists, we say the sequence formula_140 converges pointwise to formula_186.

The second one is called uniform limit, denoted

:formula_197,
:formula_198,
:formula_199, or
:formula_200,

which means:

:For each real number formula_37, there exists a natural number formula_202 such that, for every natural number formula_190 and for every natural number formula_39, we have formula_193.

Symbolically, this is:
:formula_206.

In this definition, the choice of formula_38 is independent of formula_190. In other words, the choice of formula_38 is &quot;uniformly applicable&quot; to all natural numbers formula_190. Hence, one can easily see that uniform convergence is a stronger property than pointwise convergence: the existence of uniform limit implies the existence and equality of pointwise limit:

:If formula_211 uniformly, then formula_211 pointwise.

When such a limit exists, we say the sequence formula_140 converges uniformly to formula_186.

===Iterated limit===

For a double sequence formula_165, we may take limit in one of the indices, say, formula_185, to obtain a single sequence formula_186, and then take limit in the other index, namely formula_218, to get a number formula_128. Symbolically,
:formula_220.

This limit is known as iterated limit of the double sequence. The order of taking limits may affect the result, i.e.,

:formula_221 in general.

A sufficient condition of equality is given by the Moore-Osgood theorem, which requires the limit formula_222 to be uniform in formula_150.

